<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900906-0046</DOCNO><DOCID>900906-0046.</DOCID><HL>   International:   U.S. Appears Near Accord   On Giving Arms to Israel</HL><DATE>09/06/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10</SO><CO>   MDEST</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)</IN><GV>STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Bush administration appears close toagreeing to provide Israel with a sophisticated air-defensesystem and $400 million in loan guarantees to build housingfor Soviet Jewish emigres.   Following a meeting at the State Department betweenSecretary of State James Baker and Israeli Foreign MinisterDavid Levy, an Israeli source said that the U.S. promised tosupply Israel with Patriot air-defense missiles from DefenseDepartment inventories. Israel has asked for the equipmentbecause of threats by Iraq and because the U.S. recentlyagreed to supply Saudi Arabia with over $2 billion inmilitary equipment.</LP><TEXT>   In addition, Mr. Baker said &quot;we made good progress&quot; onworking out details for providing the loan guarantees. TheIsraeli source said that an agreement in principle wasreached and that details will be worked out in the next fewdays.   Earlier this year, the administration held up Israel'srequest for the loan guarantees, insisting that Jerusalemgive assurances that they wouldn't be used to build houses inthe occupied territories.   While seeking the support of Arab governments for itsactions against Iraq, the U.S. has asked Israel to maintain alow profile in the Persian Gulf crisis. Mr. Levy is expectedto meet with President Bush today.</TEXT></DOC>